.ds n) explain_tmpfile_or_die
.cp 0  \" Solaris defaults to ''.cp 1'', sheesh.
.TH explain_tmpfile_or_die 3
.SH NAME
explain_tmpfile_or_die \- create a temporary file and report errors
.if require_index \{
.XX "explain_tmpfile_or_die(3)" \
    "create a temporary file and report errors"
.\}
.SH SYNOPSIS
#include <libexplain/tmpfile.h>
.sp 0.3
FILE *explain_tmpfile_or_die(void);
.br
FILE *explain_tmpfile_on_error(void);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]explain_tmpfile_or_die\fP function is used to call the
\f[I]tmpfile\fP(3) system call. On failure an explanation will be printed
to \f[I]stderr\fP, obtained from the \f[I]explain_tmpfile\fP(3) function,
and then the process terminates by calling \f[CW]exit(EXIT_FAILURE)\fP.
.PP
The \f[B]explain_tmpfile_on_error\fP function is used to call the
\f[I]tmpfile\fP(3) system call. On failure an explanation will be printed
to \f[I]stderr\fP, obtained from the \f[I]explain_tmpfile\fP(3) function,
but still returns to the caller.
.\" ----------------------------------------------------
.SH RETURN VALUE
The \f[B]explain_tmpfile_or_die\fP function only returns on success, see
\f[I]tmpfile\fP(3) for more information. On failure, prints an explanation
and exits, it does not return.
.PP
The \f[B]explain_tmpfile_on_error\fP function always returns the value
return by the wrapped \f[I]tmpfile\fP(3) system call.
.\" ----------------------------------------------------
.SH EXAMPLE
The \f[B]explain_tmpfile_or_die\fP function is intended to be used in a
fashion similar to the following example:
.RS
.ft CW
.nf
FILE *result = explain_tmpfile_or_die();
.fi
.ft R
.RE
